04180nmm a2200637Ia 9780801461828DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20112016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014618287 a10.7591/97808014618282doi  a(DE-B1597)478688  a(OCoLC)979577276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS832.7.A1bS55 2008eb04a320.9522221 aShipper, Apichai W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFighting for Foreigners :bImmigration and Its Impact on Japanese Democracy /cApichai W. Shipper. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough stereotypically homogenized and hostile to immigrants, Japan has experienced an influx of foreigners from Asia and Latin America in recent decades. In Fighting for Foreigners, Apichai W. Shipper details how, in response, Japanese citizens have established a variety of local advocacy groups—some faith based, some secular—to help immigrants secure access to social services, economic equity, and political rights. Drawing on his years of ethnographic fieldwork and a pragmatic account of political motivation he calls associative activism, Shipper asserts that institutions that support illegal foreigners make the most dramatic contributions to democratic multiculturalism. The changing demographics of Japan have been stimulating public discussions, the political participation of marginalized groups, and calls for fair treatment of immigrants. Nongovernmental organizations established by the Japanese have been more effective than the ethnically particular associations formed by migrants themselves, Shipper finds. Activists who initially work in concert to solve specific and local problems eventually become more ambitious in terms of political representation and opinion formation. As debates about the costs and benefits of immigration rage across the developed world, Shipper's research offers a refreshing new perspective: rather than undermining democracy in industrialized society, immigrants can make a positive institutional contribution to vibrant forms of democratic multiculturalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAliensxPolitical activityzJapan. 0aForeign workerszJapan. 0aIllegal aliensxPolitical activityzJapan. 0aIllegal immigrationzJapan. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzJapan. 0aNoncitizensxPolitical activityzJapan. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies.  aPolitical science, Japan, Japanese democracy, associative activism, democratic multiculturalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146182840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801461828/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles